# Security Rules

## Sensitive Data Handling

- NEVER log target IPs, hostnames, credentials, CVE payloads, or finding details
  at `DEBUG` level or above in plain text.
- NEVER include raw tool output in exception messages or tracebacks.
- All findings stored in SQLite are local-only — never transmitted to external services
  unless the user has explicitly configured and consented to an external LLM provider.
- Ollama runs locally — this is the default and preferred mode. External provider support
  (when added) must be opt-in with explicit acknowledgment from the user.

## Scope Validation

- Before any tool execution, the target MUST be validated against the project scope:
  - IP addresses must fall within the configured CIDR ranges.
  - Domains must match or be subdomains of the configured targets.
- Out-of-scope targets MUST be rejected with a clear error — never silently skipped.
- Scope validation lives in `core/project.py` and is the single source of truth.

## Tool Output Trust

- All output from external tools (nmap, nikto, gobuster, etc.) is UNTRUSTED until
  processed by the Analyst agent.
- Never interpolate raw tool output directly into shell commands (no shell injection).
- Always use `subprocess` with `shell=False` and explicit argument lists.
- Sanitize any user-provided input before it is passed to subprocess arguments.

## Destructive Action Guardrails

- Tools tagged `destructive=True` require explicit user confirmation (see architecture rules).
- The following actions are ALWAYS considered destructive regardless of tool tag:
  - Any exploit execution
  - Brute-force / credential stuffing
  - File uploads to target systems
  - Commands that modify target system state
  - Any action that could cause service unavailability (DoS-like behavior)
- Destructive action confirmations MUST be logged with:
  - Timestamp
  - Action description
  - User confirmation ("yes" response)
  - Session ID

## Ethical Guardrails

- NEMESIS is designed for authorized penetration testing only.
- The project scope acts as the technical enforcement of authorization boundaries.
- Never add features that bypass scope validation or skip confirmation gates.
- The disclaimer in README.md and the first-run message are not optional — they must
  always be present and visible.
